\begin_layout Standard
Three coordination mechanisms are available.
 
\series bold
Direct delegation
\series default
:
 the cognitive loop dispatches a single agent via a tool call.
 
\series bold
Parallel dispatch
\series default
:
 when the LLM requests multiple agent tool calls in one response,
 all agents run simultaneously as independent OTP processes;
 results are accumulated in any order and combined for synthesis.
 
\series bold
Agent teams
\series default
:
 coordinated groups with a shared strategy—

\family typewriter
ParallelMerge
\family default
 (all work simultaneously,
 results merged by synthesis LLM),
 
\family typewriter
TeamPipeline
\family default
 (sequential,
 each receives prior output),
 
\family typewriter
DebateAndConsensus
\family default
 (independent analyses then debate over rounds with convergence detection),
 and 
\family typewriter
LeadWithSpecialists
\family default
 (specialists work in parallel,
 then a lead synthesises).
 Teams appear as tools (prefixed 
\family typewriter
team_
\family default
) alongside individual agent tools.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When an agent completes,
 the framework populates typed 
\family typewriter
AgentFindings
\family default
 (e.g.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\family typewriter
ResearcherFindings
\family default
 with sources and dead ends,
 
\family typewriter
CoderFindings
\family default
 with files touched).
 Tool errors that occurred during the react loop are captured in 
\family typewriter
AgentSuccess.tool_errors
\family default
—
when non-empty,
 the cognitive loop prefixes a warning so the orchestrating LLM knows the result may be unreliable.
 Agent health is also pushed to the Curator's sensorium via 
\family typewriter
UpdateAgentHealth
\family default
,
 making degradation visible before the next cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Delegation depth is capped by 
\family typewriter
max_delegation_depth
\family default
 (default
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3).
 Sub-agents cannot call 
\family typewriter
request_human_input
\family default
—
they report only through their return value,
 preventing a delegated agent from hijacking the operator interaction channel.
 Active delegations are tracked on 
\family typewriter
CognitiveState
\family default
 and rendered in the sensorium's 
\family typewriter
<delegations>
\family default
 section,
 showing turn progress,
 token usage,
 and elapsed time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
comms agent
\series default
 sends and receives email with three independent safety layers:
 a hard recipient allowlist (not D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

-bypassable),
 deterministic regex rules blocking credentials and system internals,
 and agent-specific D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 features with tighter tool gate thresholds (0.30/0.50 vs the default 0.35/0.55).
 An inbox polling actor checks for new messages at a configurable interval and routes them to the cognitive loop as 
\family typewriter
SchedulerInput
\family default
,
 triggering the full autonomous evaluation stack.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Auditability and Git Backup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All runtime state is reconstructable from append-only JSONL files.
 No record is modified or deleted during normal operation;
 current state is derived by replaying operations chronologically.
 This makes forensic reconstruction straightforward:
 any fact,
 any case,
 any task can be traced to the cycle that created it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
cycle log
\series default
 (daily-rotated JSONL in 
\family typewriter
.springdrift/memory/cycle-log/
\family default
) records every LLM call,
 tool execution,
 D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 gate decision,
 and agent delegation as structured DAG nodes.
 Nodes form a parent-child tree:
 a user or scheduler cycle at the root,
 with agent sub-cycles and tool calls as descendants.
 Each node carries token counts,
 model used,
 elapsed time,
 and typed agent output.
 The Observer agent's 
\family typewriter
inspect_cycle
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
list_recent_cycles
\family default
 tools provide the agent itself with drill-down access to this telemetry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Librarian
\series default
 actor owns ETS tables that serve as a fast query cache over the JSONL stores.
 At startup,
 it replays up to 
\family typewriter
librarian_max_days
\family default
 (default
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

30) of narrative entries,
 CBR cases,
 facts,
 artifacts,
 and DAG nodes into in-memory tables.
 All memory tools query through the Librarian when available,
 falling back to direct JSONL reads when it is not running.
 New entries written by the Archivist or other subsystems are indexed immediately via notification messages,
 so the cache is always current within the session.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Housekeeping
\series default
 (
\family typewriter
narrative/housekeeping.gleam
\family default
) runs periodically to maintain memory quality.
 Three operations:
 CBR deduplication (symmetric weighted field similarity above a configurable threshold merges cases),
 case pruning (old low-confidence failures without pitfall annotations are removed),
 and fact conflict resolution (when multiple facts share a key,
 the higher-confidence value is retained).
 Fact confidence decays at read time via a half-life formula (
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}=c_{0}\cdot2^{-t/h}$
\end_inset

,
 default half-life 30
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

days),
 so stale facts naturally lose influence without requiring explicit cleanup.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\family typewriter
.springdrift/
\family default
 directory is a git repository with periodic commits and optional remote push.
 A standalone Python tool (SD
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Audit) provides a web dashboard with Chart.js visualisations for offline analysis of daily activity,
 token usage,
 D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 gate decisions,
 and outcome distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Springdrift is implemented in Gleam 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{gleam2022}
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 a statically typed language that compiles to Erlang bytecode and runs on the BEAM virtual machine.
 This choice is pragmatic,
 not aesthetic—
the BEAM and Gleam's type system provide specific properties that matter for long-lived agent systems.
 A detailed technical overview is in Appendix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:beam"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Why not Python?

\series default
 Every major agent framework (LangGraph,
 CrewAI,
 AutoGen) is Python.
 Python's strengths (ecosystem,
 LLM library support) are real,
 but for a persistent runtime that manages concurrent processes,
 handles failures during multi-step reasoning,
 and must remain auditable over weeks of operation,
 its weaknesses are structural:
 the GIL limits true concurrency,
 exception handling is advisory rather than enforced,
 and there is no supervision model for automatic failure recovery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
What the BEAM provides.

\series default
 The BEAM was designed for telecommunications systems that run continuously and handle failures gracefully.
 Each Springdrift component—
cognitive loop,
 Librarian,
 Curator,
 Archivist,
 scheduler,
 inbox poller,
 sandbox manager,
 each specialist agent—
is a supervised OTP process.
 If a process crashes,
 its supervisor restarts it according to a configured strategy (Permanent,
 Transient,
 Temporary).
 The system continues operating.
 This is not theoretical:
 during the 23-day deployment,
 714
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

LLM timeouts and multiple sub-agent crashes were handled by supervision without manual intervention (Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:runtime-chars"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 Preemptive scheduling means one stuck LLM call does not block the scheduler or inbox poller.
 Per-process garbage collection means no stop-the-world pauses during long-running operation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
What Gleam's type system prevents.

\series default
 Gleam's static types catch malformed tool call parameters,
 missing message handler variants,
 and protocol mismatches at compile time.
 The 
\family typewriter
Result
\family default
 type forces every error path to be handled explicitly—
there are no unchecked exceptions.
 For agent systems where a single unhandled error can derail a multi-step reasoning chain,
 this compounds:
 every tool call,
 every message send,
 every JSON decode is a 
\family typewriter
Result
\family default
 that the compiler requires be addressed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
State ownership.

\series default
 All cross-process communication uses typed 
\family typewriter
Subject(T)
\family default
 channels.
 No shared mutable state,
 no locks,
 no race conditions on memory access.
 The Librarian owns all ETS tables.
 The Curator owns the virtual context window.
 The scheduler owns the job state.
 Boundaries are enforced by the process model,
 not by convention.
 This is directly relevant to auditability:
 you can reason about state ownership because the architecture enforces it.
\end_layout

