\begin_layout Standard
The win comes from combining two complementary signals:
 inverted index provides fast,
 exact token matching (excels where vocabulary is distinctive:
 easy P@4 = 1.000),
 while semantic embedding captures cross-vocabulary similarity (handles ambiguity where token overlap fails).
 Not all CBR variants are good:
 CBR without embeddings (P@4 = 0.620) performs significantly worse than the baseline,
 because the recency signal injects noise uncorrelated with relevance on hard queries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The benchmark is synthetic with controlled vocabulary;
 under this relevance definition,
 the hybrid advantage may be partially attributable to lexical structure.
 A real-world evaluation would use judgement-based relevance labels.
 We compare against a dense cosine baseline rather than modern hybrid retrieval systems;
 the result should therefore be interpreted as evidence that hybrid retrieval is beneficial in this setting,
 not that this implementation is state-of-the-art.
 The hybrid lexical–semantic approach is well-established in IR research;
 our contribution is its application to structured experiential cases,
 not the retrieval technique itself.
\end_layout

