\begin_layout Subsection
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Probabilistic safety scorers are useful for screening risky actions,
 but on their own they do not provide deterministic,
 auditable resolution of normative conflicts.
 We present a deterministic normative calculus that operates after the D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 quantitative scorer 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{beach2010}
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 adding a formal decision layer for borderline cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 Discrepancy Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 evaluates features with importance and magnitude,
 producing a normalised discrepancy score:
 
\begin_inset Formula $D'=\sum(\text{importance}_{i}\times\text{magnitude}_{i})/\text{max}$
\end_inset

.
 Two configurable thresholds (defaults:
 modify 0.40,
 reject 0.75;
 the comms agent uses tighter thresholds of 0.30/0.50) determine whether to fast-accept or consult the normative calculus.
 See Appendix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A for Beach's theoretical background and worked D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 decision sheets,
 and Appendices
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

B–C for the normative calculus theory,
 worked resolutions,
 and the combined pipeline.
\end_layout

