\begin_layout Subsection
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lee Roy Beach's work on narrative thought and decision making 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{beach2010,beach1990}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 provides a descriptive account of how people actually make decisions.
 Where expected utility theory models decisions as probability-weighted outcome maximisation,
 Beach's framework models decisions as 
\series bold
compatibility tests
\series default
—
the decision maker checks whether a candidate option is compatible with their existing values,
 goals,
 and plans.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beach calls these three bodies of knowledge the decision maker's 
\emph on
images
\emph default
:
 the 
\emph on
value image
\emph default
 (principles and standards),
 the 
\emph on
trajectory image
\emph default
 (goals and desired futures),
 and the 
\emph on
strategic image
\emph default
 (plans currently being pursued).
 Each feature of a forecasted future that conflicts with an image is a 
\series bold
discrepancy
\series default
.
 The aggregate measure is D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each feature is scored on importance (how much it matters) and magnitude (how discrepant the forecast is from the desired state).
 D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 is the normalised sum:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D'=\frac{\sum_{i}\text{importance}_{i}\times\text{magnitude}_{i}}{\text{max\_importance}\times\text{max\_magnitude}\times n}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The decision maker has a 
\series bold
rejection threshold
\series default
.
 If D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 exceeds it,
 the option is rejected.
 The decision maker is not asking 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

which option is best?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

does this option violate enough of what matters to me that I should reject it?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Beach's empirical work shows this screening process is how most real-world decisions are made.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Springdrift,
 features are organised by gate (input,
 tool,
 output) and by agent (agent-specific overrides with their own feature sets and thresholds).
 This maps directly to Beach's hierarchical feature model.
\end_layout

