\begin_layout Subsection
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The normative calculus is a deterministic ethical reasoning system based on Becker's 
\emph on
A New Stoicism
\emph default
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{becker1998}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Ethical reasoning is formalised as conflict resolution between normative propositions.
 When propositions conflict,
 the calculus provides deterministic rules based on relative priority and strength.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Formal Structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The normative calculus is an interpreted axiomatic system with three components:
 normative operators,
 ordinal levels,
 and resolution axioms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Normative operators.

\series default
 Three operators express the strength of a norm.
 
\emph on
Required
\emph default
 (R):
 the proposition must be satisfied—
violation is impermissible.
 
\emph on
Ought
\emph default
 (O):
 the proposition should be satisfied—
violation is undesirable but not categorical.
 
\emph on
Indifferent
\emph default
 (I):
 the proposition carries no normative weight.
 The ranking is strict:
 R
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


