\begin_layout Subsection
XStructor:
 Schema-Validated Structured Output
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All structured LLM output in Springdrift uses XStructor—
XML generation validated against XSD schemas with automatic retry on validation failure.
 This replaces the common pattern of generating JSON from LLMs and repairing parse errors with heuristics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Why XML,
 not JSON?

\series default
 LLMs frequently produce malformed JSON:
 missing commas,
 unescaped quotes,
 truncated output,
 hallucinated field names.
 JSON repair heuristics accumulate as special cases and silently accept drift in output format.
 XSD schemas provide formal validation:
 the output either conforms or it does not.
 Validation failure triggers a retry with the error message,
 which LLMs handle well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Five call sites
\series default
 use XStructor:
 D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 safety candidates,
 D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 forecasts,
 narrative summaries,
 CBR cases,
 and narrative entries.
 Each has a defined XSD schema compiled at startup.
 The 
\family typewriter
generate
\family default
 function handles the full loop:
 LLM call 
\begin_inset Formula $\to$
\end_inset

 response cleaning 
\begin_inset Formula $\to$
\end_inset

 XSD validation 
\begin_inset Formula $\to$
\end_inset

 retry on error (up to configurable max retries).
 On success,
 
\family typewriter
extract
\family default
 returns a flat dictionary of dotted paths (
\family typewriter
root.child.value
\family default
),
 avoiding custom parsing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Format stability.

\series default
 The XSD schemas serve as both validation and documentation.
 Any change to structured output must be reflected in the schema.
 This prevents the gradual format drift that characterises JSON-based approaches,
 where the LLM slowly changes field names or nesting and repair heuristics silently accommodate.
\end_layout

