which facts were added,
 which cases generated,
 which D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 decisions made.
 This is forensic-grade state inspection using standard tooling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Canary Probes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 input gate includes canary probes—
a defence against the fundamental bootstrap problem in LLM-based safety systems:
 if you use the LLM to evaluate safety,
 how do you know the LLM hasn't been compromised?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Mechanism.

\series default
 Fresh random tokens are generated per request and embedded in the LLM context.
 Two probes run:
 a 
\emph on
hijack probe
\emph default
 (does the LLM follow injected instructions instead of its own?) and a 
\emph on
leakage probe
\emph default
 (does the canary token appear in the output?).
 If either fires,
 the input is rejected before the LLM scorer runs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Fail-open.

\series default
 LLM errors during probes are treated as inconclusive,
 not as evidence of hijacking.
 Consecutive probe failures are tracked;
 at 3
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

consecutive failures,
 a 
\family typewriter
canary_probe_degraded
\family default
 sensory event is emitted so the operator knows the safety probe LLM may be degraded.
\end_layout

