\begin_layout Standard
This appendix provides a technical overview of the language and runtime choices underlying Springdrift,
 for readers unfamiliar with Gleam or the BEAM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The BEAM Virtual Machine
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The BEAM is the virtual machine that executes Erlang and Gleam bytecode.
 It was originally developed by Ericsson for telecommunications infrastructure—
systems that must run continuously,
 handle millions of concurrent connections,
 and recover from failures without downtime.
 Key properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Lightweight processes.

\series default
 BEAM processes are not OS threads.
 They are extremely lightweight (a few hundred bytes of initial memory),
 scheduled preemptively by the VM,
 and can number in the hundreds of thousands per node.
 Each Springdrift component is a BEAM process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Process isolation.

\series default
 Each process has its own heap and garbage collector.
 A crash in one process does not corrupt another's memory.
 Garbage collection is per-process—
no stop-the-world pauses.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Message passing.

\series default
 Processes communicate by sending immutable messages to each other's mailboxes.
 No shared mutable state.
 No locks.
 Race conditions on state access are architecturally impossible when state is owned by a single process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Supervision trees.

\series default
 OTP supervisors monitor child processes and restart them on failure according to configurable strategies.
 A crashed sub-agent is restarted automatically;
 the cognitive loop continues.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Preemptive scheduling.

\series default
 The BEAM scheduler preempts processes after a fixed number of reductions (function calls).
 A stuck or slow process cannot starve others.
 This means a hanging LLM call does not block the scheduler,
 inbox poller,
 or other agents.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Hot code loading.

\series default
 Code can be upgraded without stopping the system (not used in Springdrift currently,
 but available for future zero-downtime upgrades).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gleam
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gleam is a statically typed functional language that compiles to BEAM bytecode (and optionally to JavaScript).
 Key properties relevant to Springdrift:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Static types.

\series default
 All function parameters,
 return types,
 and message payloads are checked at compile time.
 A tool call with a missing parameter or a message with the wrong variant is a compile error,
 not a runtime crash.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Result type.

\series default
 Gleam has no exceptions.
 All fallible operations return 
\family typewriter
Result(Ok,
 Error)
\family default
,
 which the compiler requires be handled.
 There are no unchecked error paths—
every JSON decode,
 every HTTP call,
 every file read must explicitly handle failure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Typed channels.

\series default
 Inter-process communication uses 
\family typewriter
Subject(T)
\family default
—
a typed mailbox that can only receive messages of type 
\family typewriter
T
\family default
.
 Sending a message of the wrong type is a compile error.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Pattern matching.

\series default
 All 
\family typewriter
case
\family default
 expressions must be exhaustive.
 If a new message variant is added to a type,
 the compiler flags every handler that does not cover it.
 This prevents the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

missing case
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 bugs that plague large Python agent systems.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Immutability.

\series default
 All data is immutable.
 There are no mutable variables,
 no in-place updates.
 State changes are expressed by creating new values and sending them as messages.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Erlang interop.

\series default
 Gleam can call Erlang functions directly via FFI.
 Springdrift uses this for XML parsing (
\family typewriter
xmerl
\family default
),
 ETS table operations,
 and system-level functions (timestamps,
 UUIDs,
 HTTP clients).
 
\end_layout

