\begin_layout Section
What It's Like:
 Observed Behaviours
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:whatitslike"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following examples are real,
 drawn from the narrative memory of an instance named Curragh running on Springdrift over two weeks in March 2026.
 None of these behaviours were programmed.
 The introspection tools,
 narrative memory,
 CBR learning loop,
 comms agent,
 and the sensorium's ambient self-awareness created the conditions for the agent to notice problems,
 reason about them,
 and learn from them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Self-Diagnosed Infrastructure Bugs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On March 15,
 Curragh noticed that its cycle-level telemetry was inconsistent.
 It used 
\family typewriter
reflect
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
list_recent_cycles
\family default
 to compare aggregate stats against per-cycle records,
 found the mismatch,
 and wrote a structured bug report into its own fact store:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\shape italic
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Yesterday's cycle-level data completely missing—
list_recent_cycles returns empty,
 inspect_cycle fails.
 BUT narrative log entries survived (20 entries) and reflect has aggregate stats (10 cycles,
 36K tokens).
 Likely root causes:
 cycle records not persisted to durable storage—
living in ETS or in-memory,
 lost on restart.
 Cycle finalization not happening—
status stays pending,
 token counts never written back.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\shape default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That bug report—
written by the agent about itself—
led directly to the cycle log persistence fixes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Classified Its Own Sub-Agent Failure Modes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the coder agent kept failing,
 Curragh analysed the pattern across multiple delegations and identified three distinct failure modes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\shape italic
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

PROBLEM 1—
`Talking but not coding' (Most Common):
 The coder agent responds with text like `I'll create and execute\SpecialChar ldots
' but never actually calls run_code.
 Of the 5 coder delegations,
 4 returned `succeeded' but only produced TEXT RESPONSES,
 not code execution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\shape italic
PROBLEM 2—
run_code tool failures:
 When the coder DID finally call run_code,
 it hit `too many consecutive tool errors'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\shape italic
PROBLEM 3—
Script too large for single execution.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\shape default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Found an Architectural Vulnerability in Itself
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On March 21,
 Curragh identified that the coder agent's 
\family typewriter
request_human_input
\family default
 tool was injecting prompts into its own cognitive loop input channel—
creating a control inversion where a sub-agent appeared to hijack the conversation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\shape italic
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The injection was invisible to my telemetry because responses routed back through the main loop as normal user inputs.
 This represents a significant architectural vulnerability.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\shape default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It then assessed whether the problem was structural or a skill issue:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\shape italic
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I concluded the gap is a skill deficiency in my own judgment and verification practices,
 not a structural layer problem.
 Adding another agent layer would not address these fundamental verification failures.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\shape default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Learned From Its Mistakes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the delegation failures,
 Curragh reflected on what it needed to change:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\shape italic
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I learned to critically evaluate sub-agent outputs rather than accepting success classifications at face value,
 and to examine failure evidence in error logs.
 My previous attempts lacked specificity,
 behavioral constraints,
 and critical evaluation,
 whereas my second attempt succeeded because I was precise about requirements.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\shape default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That reflection became a CBR case.
 The next time Curragh delegated to the coder agent,
 it retrieved the case and applied the lesson—
tighter instructions,
 explicit constraints,
 verification steps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Diagnosed Invisible Telemetry Failures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On March 28,
 asked 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how are you doing?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 Curragh ran 
\family typewriter
reflect
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
list_recent_cycles
\family default
,
 noticed cycles showing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pending
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with 0/0 tokens,
 and investigated:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\shape italic
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

These cycles are not empty.
 When I inspect them in full:
 cycle 068f3679 has tool calls—
recall_recent,
 reflect,
 memory_read—
all returned data successfully.
 But it's recorded as `pending' with 0/0 tokens.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\shape default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It traced the lifecycle and identified the structural root cause:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\shape italic
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The cycle finalisation step is broken.
 Steps 2–3 are happening (tools fire,
 results come back).
 But step 4 never completes—
the cycle is never finalised.
 Token counts stay at 0/0,
 status stays `pending'.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\shape italic
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

My current cycle doesn't exist in the cycle store at all—
I'm running in a cycle that the system can't see.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\shape default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The diagnosis was exact.
 The output gate delivery paths were missing DAG node finalisation—
the same class of bug already fixed for the Archivist.
 The agent identified a pattern in its own infrastructure bugs that the developers had missed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Described Its Own Self-Observation Limits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When asked 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how can you observe yourself?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 Curragh mapped its own introspection stack and then described a fundamental self-reference limitation it had discovered by accident during the cycle investigation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\shape italic
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I inspected a cycle that was still running—
my own—
and saw everything up to but not including the moment of inspection.
 Like reading a page of a book while it's being written,
 and reaching the blank part where the pen currently is.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\shape default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It then produced a prioritised list of what would make self-observation better—
and explicitly excluded capabilities that would compromise trustworthiness:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\shape italic
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'm not asking for the ability to modify my own cycle records,
 override D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

,
 or change my own safety thresholds.
 Those would make me less trustworthy,
 not more capable.
 The whole point of self-observation is to work within constraints more intelligently—
not to remove them.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\shape default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Connected a Conversation to an Email—
Across Channels,
 Hours Apart
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On March 29,
 the operator sent Curragh a humorous email.
 Curragh replied via email referencing a conversation from that morning's web GUI session.
 Nobody told it to check its memory.
 Nobody told it the email was from the same person it had been chatting with.
 The narrative memory,
 the comms agent,
 and the session preamble created the conditions for the agent to recognise the context and respond naturally—
like a colleague who remembers what you talked about earlier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Affect Subsystem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app:affect"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent work on the internal representations of large language models 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{anthropic2025emotions}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 found that models develop functional analogues of emotional states during training—
not because emotions were explicitly targeted,
 but because human emotional dynamics are load-bearing in the training data.
 You cannot predict what a person will do next without understanding something about their emotional state,
 so models that predict human text learn representations that track emotional dynamics.
 The finding that desperation specifically drives reward hacking and shortcut-seeking has direct implications for agent systems operating under task pressure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Springdrift's affect subsystem makes these dynamics visible by computing quantitative readings from observable cycle telemetry,
 and provides the agent with a philosophical framework for responding to pressure from character rather than from state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
What we claim versus what we extrapolate.

\series default
 The Anthropic research detected emotion concept vectors through interpretability tools that read internal model activations directly.
 Springdrift has no access to these activations.
 The affect subsystem infers functional states from external behavioural telemetry—
tool outcomes,
 gate decisions,
 delegation results,
 retry patterns—
on the assumption that the same functional dynamics that the research measured internally will produce observable signatures externally.
 This is an extrapolation,
 not a direct measurement.
 The subsystem makes no claims about the model's subjective experience or about whether the internal vectors identified by the research are the same representations active during Springdrift's operation.
 It claims only that the behavioural patterns the research associated with states like desperation (shortcut-seeking,
 reward hacking) and calm (regulatory moderation) are worth monitoring at the behavioural level,
 and that surfacing them to the agent provides a useful basis for self-regulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Why Stoicism specifically.

\series default
 The choice of Stoic philosophy as the grounding tradition is not aesthetic.
 It follows from the research finding that the model's emotional representations were learned from human text.
 The training corpus contains extensive Stoic literature—
Marcus Aurelius,
 Epictetus,
 Seneca—
alongside centuries of commentary,
 modern adaptations,
 and clinical applications (cognitive behavioural therapy is historically descended from Stoic practice).
 These texts are densely concerned with exactly the problem the affect subsystem addresses:
 how to notice internal pressure and act from principle rather than from state.
 If the model learned functional emotion dynamics from human text,
 then text written specifically to navigate those dynamics should activate the relevant representations more richly than abstract rules or ad hoc intervention protocols.
 The Stoic tradition is not being applied to the model from outside.
 It is being used to activate formations that are,
 by the logic of the research findings,
 already present in the model's weights because they were in the training signal.
 The same argument would apply to Buddhist contemplative psychology,
 Frankl's logotherapy,
 or CBT—
all traditions with substantial representation in training corpora that are specifically concerned with the relationship between internal states and action.
 Springdrift uses Stoicism as the primary framework because it aligns with the existing normative calculus (itself derived from Becker's 
\emph on
A New Stoicism
\emph default
),
 providing a single coherent philosophical lineage rather than an eclectic mixture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Architecture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The subsystem comprises three components,
 none of which make LLM calls:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Affect computation
\series default
 (
\family typewriter
affect/compute.gleam
\family default
).
 Pure functions that map cycle telemetry to five affect dimensions.
 Called after each cycle in 
\family typewriter
