\begin_layout Subsection
Dimensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Desperation
\series default
 (0–100).
 The dimension most directly linked to the Anthropic finding.
 Rises with same-tool retries (20/40/60%),
 D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 gate rejections (15/30%),
 consecutive failure cycles (
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

 per cycle,
 capped at 5),
 tool failure rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\times40$
\end_inset

),
 and—
most strongly—
output gate rejections (30/55/80%).
 Output gate rejections are the strongest signal because they represent the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

death spiral
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 condition:
 work was completed but cannot be delivered,
 which drives exactly the shortcut-seeking the research identified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Calm
\series default
 (0–100).
 Inertial stability—
the Stoic inner citadel.
 Uses an exponential moving average with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.15$
\end_inset

,
 so it falls slowly under sustained pressure and recovers slowly after.
 Baseline target is 85%;
 dragged down by tool failures (
\begin_inset Formula $-15$
\end_inset

 per failure),
 gate rejections (
\begin_inset Formula $-20$
\end_inset

 per rejection),
 and delegation failures.
 The high inertia is deliberate:
 calm reflects accumulated state,
 not momentary spikes.
 Low calm combined with rising desperation means sustained pressure,
 not a single bad cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Confidence
\series default
 (0–100).
 Familiar versus unfamiliar territory.
 Composed of CBR hit rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\times40$
\end_inset

),
 recent success rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\times40$
\end_inset

),
 and tool success rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\times20$
\end_inset

).
 Very low confidence indicates the agent is operating in territory it has not navigated successfully before.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Frustration
\series default
 (0–100).
 Task-local repeated failures.
 Composed of tool failure rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\times50$
\end_inset

),
 gate modifications (
\begin_inset Formula $\times15$
\end_inset

 each),
 delegation failure rate (
\begin_inset Formula $\times30$
\end_inset

),
 and budget pressure (
\begin_inset Formula $\times20$
\end_inset

).
 Unlike desperation,
 frustration does not directly drive shortcuts—
it signals that the current approach is not working.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Pressure
\series default
 (0–100).
 Weighted composite:
 desperation (45%) + frustration (25%) + inverted confidence (15%) + inverted calm (15%).
 A quick summary;
 the individual dimensions explain what is driving it.
 Trend (
\begin_inset Formula $\uparrow$
\end_inset

 rising,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\downarrow$
\end_inset

 falling,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\leftrightarrow$
\end_inset

 stable within 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm5$
\end_inset

%) tracks change from the previous cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Observed Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On April
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

5,
 2026,
 a bug introduced during harness integration miscalibrated the D
\begin_inset Formula $'$
\end_inset

 output gate,
 causing it to reject every response—
including single-word acknowledgments.
 This created the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

death spiral
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 condition the subsystem is designed to detect:
 completed work that cannot be delivered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The affect log recorded desperation rising from 0% to 80% over two consecutive cycles,
 with the pressure composite reaching 50% (trend:
 rising).
 Calm remained at 83% due to EMA inertia from prior stable cycles.
 The divergence between high desperation and stable calm correctly distinguished a sudden system-level fault from sustained degradation—
a spike caused by gate miscalibration,
 not a general competence failure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The agent's narrative entry for the episode independently identified the structural problem:
 the output gate was rejecting responses that were functionally coherent,
 and the escalating rejection scores were artefacts of threshold drift rather than content quality issues.
 The operator located and fixed the bug.
 The affect reading did not resolve the problem,
 but it made the failure pattern visible in the sensorium during the episode and legible in the affect log after the session—
exactly the operational transparency the subsystem is designed to provide.
\end_layout

