\end_inset

,
 provides the system with a quantitative view of its own operational state.
 Together these enable proactive behaviour:
 the system notices when something is overdue,
 when a sub-agent is degraded,
 or when its own performance is deteriorating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Forensic accountability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cycle log records every LLM call,
 tool invocation,
 gate decision,
 and agent delegation as a directed acyclic graph.
 Any decision can be reconstructed after the fact by walking the DAG from the root cycle to the leaf nodes.
 The normative calculus produces named axiom trails for every safety decision.
 The narrative memory captures the system's own assessment of what happened each cycle,
 including honest reporting of failures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Relationship continuity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The case-based reasoning system (hybrid retrieval with inverted index,
 semantic embeddings,
 and utility scoring) captures reusable problem-solution-outcome patterns.
 The task appraisal system generates pre-mortems before complex work and post-mortems after completion,
 feeding lessons learned back into the case base.
 Over the 23-day deployment,
 the system accumulated 483 CBR cases,
 117 narrative threads,
 and a persistent fact store —
 building a working model of the operator's goals,
 communication preferences,
 and recurring research interests.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Honest assessment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Springdrift is a prototype,
 not a validated product.
 The 23-day deployment revealed significant architectural failures alongside the successes:
 a D
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
prime
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 output gate rejection cascade that rendered the system unable to deliver any output for several hours;
 an email re-injection loop caused by a flawed deduplication mechanism;
 and an affect monitoring system that failed to detect the rejection cascade because it lacked visibility into output gate decisions (subsequently fixed).
 These failures are as instructive as the successes.
 They demonstrate that the Artificial Retainer architecture is buildable,
 but that the engineering challenges —
 particularly around authority calibration and self-monitoring under adversarial conditions —
 are substantial and unsolved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What Springdrift demonstrates is that the six structural properties of the Artificial Retainer can coexist in a running system.
 Whether they coexist 
\emph on
well enough
\emph default
 to constitute a useful retainer relationship is a question that requires longer deployment,
 systematic evaluation,
 and —
 most importantly —
 the principal's own judgment about whether the relationship is compounding in the way the concept promises.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Limitations and Open Questions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Artificial Retainer concept is an extrapolation from one prototype system over a limited deployment period.
 Several questions remain open:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Authority calibration.

\series default
 How should the scope of authority be defined,
 adjusted,
 and audited over time?
 The Springdrift deployment demonstrated that miscalibrated authority (an over-aggressive output gate) can be worse than no authority at all.
 The dynamics of human-AI authority negotiation are not well studied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Relationship decay.

\series default
 Does the value of accumulated context degrade as the principal's situation changes?
 A retained solicitor who has not been briefed in a year may have stale assumptions.
 The same applies to an Artificial Retainer.
 Springdrift implements confidence decay on its fact store,
 but the broader question of relationship staleness is unaddressed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Transfer and succession.

\series default
 Can a retainer relationship be transferred to a new system or a new principal?
 What is preserved and what is lost?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Affect and self-monitoring.

\series default
 The functional emotion research
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "anthropic2026emotions"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 suggests that internal states influence behaviour causally.
 The Springdrift implementation infers these states from external telemetry —
 an engineering extrapolation,
 not a validated measurement.
 Whether this approximation is sufficient for reliable self-monitoring under adversarial conditions is unknown.
 The deployment revealed a specific failure:
 the affect system reported calm readings while the output gate was in a catastrophic rejection cascade,
 because the affect dimensions did not include output gate decisions as a signal source.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Social and legal status.

\series default
 Working animals have legal recognition and social norms governing their use.
 Artificial Retainers currently have neither.
 As these systems become more capable and more deeply embedded in professional workflows,
 the question of their status —
 legal,
 ethical,
 and social —
 will require attention.
 
\end_layout

